04963nam a22006855i 9780226669199DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20202020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226669199  a(DE-B1597)575530  a(OCoLC)1199891040  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aML410.B42bK606 2021 7aMUS0000002bisacsh04a780.922231 aKinderman, William, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeethoven :bA Political Artist in Revolutionary Times /cWilliam Kinderman. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b4 color plates, 20 halftones, 26 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tI A Tale of Two Cities: Bonn to Vienna -- tII The Sublime and Inverted Sublime -- tIII Beethoven in Heiligenstadt -- tIV Path to the Eroica -- tV Leonore as “Angel of Freedom” -- tVI From Grätz to Wagram and Leipzig -- tVII A Double Chill: Beethoven in Metternich’s Vienna -- tVIII Then and Now: The Ninth Symphony -- tAcknowledgments -- tIllustrations and Examples -- tNote about Abbreviations -- tSources and Documents -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe have long regarded Beethoven as a great composer, but we rarely appreciate that he was also an eminently political artist. This book unveils the role of politics in his oeuvre, elucidating how the inherently political nature of Beethoven’s music explains its power and endurance. William Kinderman presents Beethoven as a civically engaged thinker faced with severe challenges. The composer lived through many tumultuous events—the French Revolution, the rise and fall of Napoleon Bonaparte, and the Congress of Vienna among them. Previous studies of Beethoven have emphasized the importance of his personal suffering and inner struggles; Kinderman instead establishes that musical tensions in works such as the Eroica, the Appassionata, and his final piano sonata in C minor reflect Beethoven’s attitudes toward the political turbulence of the era. Written for the 250th anniversary of his birth, Beethoven takes stock of the composer’s legacy, showing how his idealism and zeal for resistance have ensured that masterpieces such as the Ninth Symphony continue to inspire activists around the globe. Kinderman considers how the Fifth Symphony helped galvanize resistance to fascism, how the Sixth has energized the environmental movement, and how Beethoven’s civic engagement continues to inspire in politically perilous times. Uncertain times call for ardent responses, and, as Kinderman convincingly affirms, Beethoven’s music is more relevant today than ever before.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBeethoven, Ludwig van,-1770-1827-Criticism and interpretation. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  aAppassionata.  aBeethoven.  aEnlightenment.  aEroica.  aFrench Revolution.  aNinth Symphony.  aSchiller.  apolitical resistance.  apolitical symbolism.  asublime.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069309640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226669199423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226669199/original  a978-3-11-069309-6  Univ